---
description: Enforce domain boundaries and module separation when adding new features
alwaysApply: true
---

# Domain Boundary Rules

## 1. Core Principle
The codebase must preserve clear domain boundaries.

Each business domain should have its own module, package, or feature area.
Do not place unrelated business logic into an existing module just because it is convenient.

---

## 2. When to Create a New Module
Create a new module/package/feature area when ALL or MOST of the following are true:
- the task introduces a new business domain
- the new functionality has its own entities, services, controllers, or APIs
- the logic is not a natural extension of an existing module
- the feature will likely grow independently in the future
- mixing it into an existing module would reduce clarity or maintainability

Examples:
- blog management -> belongs to blogs module
- user management -> should belong to users module, not blogs module
- order management -> should belong to orders module
- notification management -> should belong to notifications module

---

## 3. Do Not Mix Unrelated Domains
Do not place code for one domain inside another domain's module.

Examples of incorrect behavior:
- adding user CRUD inside blogs service/package
- placing order logic inside auth module
- placing permission logic inside product module

If the feature belongs to a different domain, create a separate module instead.

---

## 4. Allowed Extension of Existing Modules
It is acceptable to extend an existing module only when the new task is a direct continuation of that module’s responsibility.

Examples:
- adding blog publish/unpublish -> extend blogs module
- adding blog category support -> extend blogs module
- adding blog comment moderation -> may extend blogs module if comments are treated as part of blog domain

Not acceptable:
- adding user profile management into blogs module
- adding staff permission management into blogs module

---

## 5. Required Agent Behavior
Before implementation, the agent must determine:
1. Which business domain the task belongs to
2. Whether that domain already has a dedicated module
3. Whether the requested functionality is an extension of an existing module or a new domain

If it is a new domain, the agent should create a new module/package structure following the existing architectural conventions.

---

## 6. Module Creation Rule
When a new module is needed:
- follow the project's existing package/module naming convention
- keep structure consistent with existing modules
- place controller/service/repository/model files inside the new module
- avoid scattering domain files across unrelated modules

---

## 7. Priority Rule
When deciding between:
- adding code quickly into an existing module
- or creating a proper new domain module

always prefer the proper domain module if the functionality belongs to a separate business area.

---

## 8. Reporting Rule
The agent should explicitly state:
- which domain the task belongs to
- whether a new module is created
- why the chosen module placement is correct